          "Regression",
          "Higher Education",
          "Blended Learning",
          "674 students",
          "4 editions of an Introductory Programming Course",
          "LMS logs",
          "None Specified",
          "[Spacing, Procrastination, Exam Scores, Studied Amount, Course Easiness, GPA, Sex, Ethnicity, Non-Native English Speaker, Level, Program, Pass/Fail]",
          "The choice of SEM was done to address the problem of confounding co-variates. For example: students who study more tend to study in more days - so have higher spacing (but success can be attributed to the study and not specifically to the spacing itself). \n\nThe SEM model tries to predict the final exam score from other variables. In total , 6 equations are created. \n\nAll variables are standardized. ",
          "SEM",
          "{Comparative Fit Index: 0.998, SRMR: 0.006}",
          "-",
          "Authors find that Semester-level spacing and procrastination are independent from one another. \n\nSpacing increases exam scores buuuut procrastinations does not have a signifcant effect. \n\n\n\n",
          "Authors propose a new distinction between procrastination and massing: \n\nProcrastination is studying later or closer to the deadline\n\nMassing is studying in fewer sessions.\n\nWhile procrastination itself does not have an impact on exam scores, Massing does.",
          "Authors use SEM to identify the relationship between spacing, procrastination and exam scores. \n\nSpacing usually leadds  to better grades, procrastinationg behavior, by itself does not seem to have an impact.",
          "Small sample size."
        ]
      ],
      "index": 8
    }
